s as philosophy, literature and cultural criticism to run interference with (and offer alternatives to) the instrumentalist logic and predatory structures that are reducing the world to a collection of quantifiable and tradeable resources. The book will be of interest to cultural historians and theorists, media studies scholars, political scientists, and students of French and Francophone literature and culture on both sides of the Atlantic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aContinental philosophy. 0aCritical theory. 0aGeneral Strike, France, 1968. 0aSocial change. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aHistory : Radical History. 4aLiterature : Comparative Literature. 4aLiterature : Literary Theory. 4aPhilosophy : Post Structuralism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aBaetens, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroqua, Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastillo, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastillo, David R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aConsenstein, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuller, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaines, Jane M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaute, Lucile, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLévesque-Jalbert, Émile, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoreiras, Alberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNegrete, Fernanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPier